React heavily uses ES6 (ECMAScript 2015) features. Understanding these is essential for modern React development.

**ES6 Variables (let and const):**
```javascript
// let - can be reassigned
let count = 0;
count = 1;

// const - cannot be reassigned
const name = 'Alice';
// name = 'Bob'; // Error

// const with objects
const user = { name: 'Alice' };
user.name = 'Bob'; // OK - object properties can change
```

**Arrow Functions:**
```javascript
// Traditional function
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

// Arrow function
const add = (a, b) => a + b;

// Arrow function with single parameter
const square = x => x * x;

// Arrow function with no parameters
const greet = () => 'Hello!';
```

**Template Literals:**
```javascript
const name = 'Alice';
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`;
```

**Destructuring:**
```javascript
// Array destructuring
const [a, b] = [1, 2];

// Object destructuring
const { name, age } = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };

// Destructuring in function parameters
function greet({ name }) {
  console.log(`Hello, ${name}!`);
}
```

**Spread Operator:**
```javascript
// Array spread
const arr1 = [1, 2];
const arr2 = [...arr1, 3, 4]; // [1, 2, 3, 4]

// Object spread
const obj1 = { name: 'Alice' };
const obj2 = { ...obj1, age: 25 }; // { name: 'Alice', age: 25 }
```

**ES6 Classes:**
```javascript
class Person {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet() {
    return `Hello, ${this.name}!`;
  }
}

const person = new Person('Alice');
console.log(person.greet());
```

**Array Methods:**
```javascript
// map
const doubled = [1, 2, 3].map(x => x * 2); // [2, 4, 6]

// filter
const evens = [1, 2, 3, 4].filter(x => x % 2 === 0); // [2, 4]

// reduce
const sum = [1, 2, 3].reduce((acc, x) => acc + x, 0); // 6

// find
const found = [1, 2, 3].find(x => x === 2); // 2
```

**Ternary Operator:**
```javascript
const age = 18;
const canVote = age >= 18 ? 'Yes' : 'No';
```

Components are the building blocks of React applications.

**Functional Component:**
```jsx
function Welcome() {
  return <h1>Hello, World!</h1>;
}

export default Welcome;
```

**App Component:**
```jsx
import React from 'react';
import './App.css';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <header className="App-header">
        <h1>Welcome to React</h1>
        <p>Start editing to see some magic happen!</p>
      </header>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

**Component Rules:**
- Component names must start with uppercase
- Components return JSX
- Components can be reused throughout the app
- Each component manages its own state

JSX is a syntax extension for JavaScript that looks similar to HTML.

**What is JSX?**
- JavaScript XML
- Allows writing HTML in JavaScript
- Transpiled to JavaScript by Babel
- Makes React code more readable

**JSX Examples:**
```jsx
// JSX
const element = <h1>Hello, World!</h1>;

// Equivalent JavaScript
const element = React.createElement('h1', null, 'Hello, World!');
```

**JSX Rules:**
```jsx
// Must have one parent element
return (
  <div>
    <h1>Title</h1>
    <p>Content</p>
  </div>
);

// Or use Fragment (React 16+)
return (
  <>
    <h1>Title</h1>
    <p>Content</p>
  </>
);
```

**Expressions in JSX:**
```jsx
const name = 'John';
const element = <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;

const sum = 5 + 3;
const element = <p>Result: {sum}</p>;
```

**Attributes in JSX:**
```jsx
// HTML attributes use camelCase
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description" />
<button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</button>
<input type="text" placeholder="Enter text" />
```

Learn how to render React components to the DOM.

**Rendering to DOM:**
```jsx
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(<App />);
```

**Multiple Components:**
```jsx
// Header.js
function Header() {
  return <header>My Website</header>;
}

// Footer.js
function Footer() {
  return <footer>© 2024</footer>;
}

// App.js
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <main>
        <h1>Welcome</h1>
      </main>
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Component Composition:**
```jsx
function Card({ title, content }) {
  return (
    <div className="card">
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{content}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Card title="Card 1" content="Content 1" />
      <Card title="Card 2" content="Content 2" />
    </div>
  );
}
```
